What does it take to give a supercar its unique sound? As you might expect, it's more than just the engine.

Everything has to be considered when engineering a cars' audio character. And for the McLaren Artura, we pushed ourselves to the limit of what was possible with technology today.

The result is a car that has a hugely diverse sound, capable of being scintillating at the top of the rev range, but comfortable while cruising.

How did we do it? Laurence Reucroft, Senior Project Engineer explains...

Did you know, the new Longtail active rear wing is 20% larger than the 720S Spider’s. With a revised profile to maximise downforce in corners, and reduce stopping distances. Our incredible engineers also created the bespoke carbon fibre front floor, which increases front downforce and maintains it during high-speed braking.​

#McLaren765LT #McLaren765LTSpider #Supercar #McLaren

node.text:
The immense performance and dynamic prowess of the new McLaren 765LT Spider, are enhanced by three compelling factors: the strength of its MonoCage II-S structure, the game-changing design of its one-piece Retractable Hard Top roof, and the ongoing determination of McLaren engineers to pursue the company’s philosophy of super-lightweight engineering.​

#McLaren765LT #McLaren765LTSpider #Supercar #McLaren

node.text:
Did you know, the 765LT Spider boasts, 0-60mph in 2.7 seconds, 0-100km/h (62mph) in 2.8 seconds and 0-200km/h (124mph) in 7.2 seconds.​

#McLaren765LT #McLaren765LTSpider #Supercar #McLaren ​

node.text:
Did you know, the carbon fibre-shelled race seats fitted as standard are together 18kg lighter than the 720S sports seats. First seen on the McLaren P1™, the seats feature a lightweight Alcantara® covering, which also appears on the steering wheel, dashboard and doors.​

#McLaren765LT #McLaren765LTSpider #Supercar #McLaren ​

“The stretched silhouette that enhances aerodynamic performance and the honed physique that improves downforce and cooling – especially on track – immediately identify the new 765LT Spider as a car that will deliver on the promise of the purest driving thrills.” ​

Rob Melville​
Design Director ​

​
#McLaren765LT #765LTSpider #Supercar #McLaren

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by McLaren Automotive on July 28, 2021. May be an image of car and road.

node.text:
The bespoke carbon fibre body panels, rear bodywork mesh and glazing look breathtaking. Their functional performance is equally impressive. They comprise 20kg of an overall 80kg weight saving and deliver 25% more downforce. ​

#McLaren765LT #765LTSpider #Supercar #McLaren

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by McLaren Automotive on July 27, 2021. May be an image of car.

node.text:
The McLaren 765LT Spider's bespoke carbon fibre body is carved and sculpted to increase downforce. And improve cooling. Its profile is elongated and minimal. ​
​
Lowered front suspension and a wider front track add purposeful aggression. Dramatic side air intakes are inspired by the legendary 675LT Spider. All-new super-lightweight 10-spoke alloy wheels and a carbon fibre active rear wing are McLaren design at its functionally beautiful best. The essence of LT.​
​
#McLaren765LT #765LTSpider #Supercar

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by McLaren Automotive on July 27, 2021. May be an image of car.

node.text:
At McLaren, we embrace the challenge and relish the unknown. Longtail models personify this spirit. Our most extreme, driver-focused, pure performance cars. With a proud lineage.​
​
The new 765LT Spider is the latest in this exclusive line.​
​
#McLaren765LT #765LTSpider #Supercar

node.text:
The 765LT is a car bred for the track, but is suited just as well to the road. We wanted to optimise the driving experience in either arena, which means its speedo has two faces. Outside of track mode you’re treated to a full digital readout. Here you’re given speed, revs, fuel, nav… anything you could want. Notice the layout of the rev counter and speedo? Looks like the 12C, right? That’s not an accident. 
 
In track mode it’s a different story. The speedo panel folds away leaving a smaller display with only the very essential numbers on display: revs, speed, and gear. When you’re hammering around a circuit, too much information can distract from the business at hand, so we kept it to just the essentials. 

#McLarenEvolution
#Supercar #McLaren

For our first Ultimate Series car, the P1, we knew that drivers would want to have as much information on show as clearly as possible. With a hybrid system and battery levels to keep an eye on, on top of fuel, tyre pressures, drive modes, and, of course, your speed, having a large, clear display was essential. Here, we went without the analogue drama of the 12C, instead giving drivers an all-digital display to ensure the right information was in the right place at the right time. 

#McLarenEvolution
#Supercar #McLaren

node.text:
With the 12C, our first road car since the F1, we knew the speedo was going to have a lot of attention paid to it. Not just from the drivers who’d be spending their time behind the wheel, but from people who wanted to enjoy the detail McLaren put into its new cars. 

We wanted to make information key here, with displays either side of the central, show stopping rev counter displaying relevant figures. The speedo itself is digital, so you’ve no excuse for not knowing how quickly you’re going. 

#McLarenEvolution
